ABSTRACT

With increasing concerns over the effects of climate change, coupled with rising operation costs, many U.S. colleges and universities are making an effort to improve their energy efficiency and sustainability. Smith College is one such institution, and while it has implemented an energy production method that greatly reduces its energy expenditures and improved its efficiency, there is always room for improvement. This study sought to examine possible patterns in energy use relating to three factors –weather, day of the week and student activity, which were then broken down into more specific subcategories– in order to provide a foundation for establishing further efficiency practices on campus. Using linear regression models and an ANOVA test, only one statistically significant relationship was found across 15 categories: there is a reduction in energy consumption associated with in-term and between-term vacations.

INTRODUCTION AND BACKGROUND

Many colleges in the U.S. are working toward using energy more efficiently and improving their sustainability practices.[1] This approach benefits schools in a variety of ways: helping to manage costs[2]; attracting incoming students –in a 2014 study by the Princeton Review, over half of the incoming freshman surveyed said that “environmental issues” would contribute to their “decision to apply or attend”)[3]; reducing consumption to safeguard energy security and mollify extreme cost spikes in an era when critical global energy sources are affected by political instability (i.e. Russia and The Middle East)[4]; making substantial contributions to reducing greenhouse gas emissions that lead to climate change[5].

Smith College has implemented many strategies to improve efficiency and sustainability, the most significant of which is the co-generation turbine power facility. The energy plant turns natural gas into electricity while harnessing thermal energy (which would typically go to waste) for heating and cooling purposes. Since the plant began operating in 2007, Smith College has increased its “energy use efficiency from 45%… to as much as 85%”[6], and it now provides almost all of the energy the campus requires during the academic year.

While these improvements are admirable, more can be done to improve the college’s energy efficiency. An important first step in creating more efficient practices is to understand patterns of energy use. There are many factors that might relate to energy consumption. Our study examines three such factors: weather, day of the week and student activities. Is there a correlation between energy consumption, weather, student activities (such as exams and vacations) and specific days of the week?

In this observational study, we looked at data for the year 2014 from the co-generation plant, the academic calendar and weather conditions on a day-to-day basis. We formed regression models to examine the data for significant relationships.

DATA

The data was obtained from the Smith College’s Chief Engineer Chuck Dougherty and included the amount of electricity generated and the amount of electricity exported to the grid (ISO New England) measured in megawatts (MW). Electrical consumption, the test statistic, was calculated by finding the difference between the amount of electricity generated each day and the amount “sold back” to the grid (the surplus).
The initial models included test statistic data from days that the cogeneration plant did not generate enough electricity to meet the campus need. Data from such days could not be analyzed because consumption could not be calculated accurately. We did not have access for data on the electricity purchased from the grid on these days. These data points were removed from the dataset and a new data set was created, called projectdata2.

Also included are the averages for the categorical variables; ExamWeek, Vacation, JTerm, and Weekday. We excluded the variable Snowday because there was only one snow day to account for during this academic year. There is data for steam production included in the dataset, but we did not include this variable because it’s likely correlated with Electrical Generation and would therefore would violate the requirement for independence between variables.

Unfortunately, the variance was not constant and the data was not normal. It was determined that the data could be modeled using multiple linear regression. This is likely because the variables with low enough p-values to be considered in the linear regression model were categorical variables, and at least one numerical variable would be needed for a linear regression model. In addition, the data was not normal and no amount of manipulation could make it normal.

If the data were normal and this model were valid, we would be able to conclude that:

On average, the electrical consumption decreases by 5.93 MW on vacation days when fewer students are on campus and, in reference to Fridays, decreases by 0.14 MW on Mondays, decreases by 3.72 MW on Saturdays, decreases by 1.0 MW on Sundays, increases by 2.45 MW on Thursdays, increases by 1.73 MW on Tuesdays and increases by 1.93 MW on Wednesdays. On a Friday that’s not a vacation day, the average consumption is 62.3 MW.

Since the data could not be modeled using linear regression, the categorical variables Vacation and Weekday were examined.

bwplot(projectdata2$Consumption ~ projectdata2$Vacation)

t.test(projectdata2$Consumption ~ projectdata2$Vacation)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  projectdata2$Consumption by projectdata2$Vacation
## t = 6.051, df = 165.063, p-value = 9.357e-09
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  4.111338 8.093941
## sample estimates:
##  mean in group no mean in group yes 
##          62.35055          56.24791

The following hypothesis tests were used to examine the categorical variable Vacation:

H0: The true difference of the means is equal to 0

HA: The true difference of the means is not equal to 0

Based on the t-test, there is a statistically significant difference between vacation days and non-vacation days. H0 is rejected in favor of HA, since a mean of 0 does not fall into the confidence interval [4.11, 8.09]. The differences in the means cannot be explained by chance.

Thus…

On average, the campus consumes more electricity on non-vacation days.

bwplot(projectdata2$Consumption ~ projectdata2$Weekday)

anovatest <- aov(projectdata2$Consumption ~ projectdata2$Weekday)
summary(anovatest)
##                       Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)  
## projectdata2$Weekday   6    951  158.55   2.291 0.0364 *
## Residuals            222  15365   69.21                 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Using a significance level of 0.05, at least one mean for the variable weekday is different. However, after accounting for Bonferroni’s correction on the significance level (0.00238 for 6 degrees of freedom), the p-value is not within the threshold and it can be concluded that there is no statistically significant difference in the weekday variable, though there is slight variation in the plot. A statistically significant relationship was found between Consumption and Vacation, but not between Consumption and any of the other variables examined.

CONCLUSION

Our research looked for correlations between energy consumption at Smith College and three factors that might influence consumption amounts –weather, student activities and day of the week– using linear regression models and an ANOVA test. Each successive regression model was adjusted to address issues with the previous model –removing statistically insignificant relationships and from the analysis and data that did not provide relevant information.
Despite efforts to improve the models, conditions for regression were not met and only one statistically significant relationship was found: there is a negative correlation between energy consumption and vacation days. In other words, Smith College Campus uses less energy when students are on break. While this finding is reasonable, it does not provide helpful information for further improving Smith College’s energy efficiency and sustainability as we had hoped.
There may be confounding variables for which we did not account, such as events at the conference center, January graduation and other activities that might affect energy consumption. The fact that we could not find a direct relationship between temperature and energy consumption, a correlation that very likely exists but did not appear in our analysis, supports the suspicion that there is a mitigating influence at work. Further investigation of these topics may include some improvements to our data gathering, such as gaining access to data for the days on which Smith bought power form the grid, data on other types of students activities (sporting events, political rallies, orientation days, etc.), or subcategories of energy consumption by campus building.
